<H1 ALIGN=Center><B>Greek and Amazon Festivals</B></H1><br>
<P ALIGN=Center><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>January Gaia</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
January 1st ~     Gamelia Festival *Gamelia is one of the names of Hera, the queen of      heaven of the Greeks. On this day marriages were celebrated, because it was a lucky day to tie the knot. <BR><br>
<BR><br>
January 5th ~     Kore's Day *Hail to Kore' (kor-ay), the Divine Maiden, i.e. Persephone.  Women adorned her statue with beautiful jewels and carried it around in the cities of the Mediterranean and the Near East, also carrying it around in their homes seven times for protection from evil.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
January 6th ~     Feast of Kore' *Nocturnal theatrical rites and feasting were held in honor of Kore'.  A group of torchbearers brought a wooden goddess statue, adorned in gold on a litter and carried around the temple seven times.  Seven is the lucky number for success.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
January 21st~    Feast of Gaia *Feasting and celebration of the goddess whom all life sprung from.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>February Demeter</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
February 1st ~     The Lesser Eleusinian Mysteries *This was an elaborate preparation for spiritual initiation of the young women.  The youth would dress in white and attend the priestesses in the temples.  The Women would celebrate themselves and share beautiful meals with each other.  It was the First Festival of the year in celebration of Demeter and the Eleusinian Mysteries.<BR><br>
<BR><H2 ALIGN=Center><B>March Kore'</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
March 9th ~     Celebration of Aphrodite and her lover Adonis *Couples celebrate with lovemaking.  Adorning their beds in flowers and a dinner with just the two of them.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
March 11sth ~     Holiday of Cybele *A day of picnicking, drinking, lying on the grass, and making merry.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
March 19th ~     Quintaria: Festival of Athena *On the evening of the first day of her festival, there was a footrace with torches.  On the second day, people competed with each other in gymnastics.  On the third day, there was a musical competition and song festival with harps, flutes, and drums to celebrate the Goddess's accomplishments.  On the fourth day, poets competed with each other in plays.  The last day, a satire was produced in honor of Athena, since laughter and wit were Athena's gifts.  <BR><br>
The winners won a crow of olives from Athena's sacred tree and a flask of oil for sacred use.  The Quintaria was closed by a giant procession, where Athena's peplus, or sacred garment, was carried by the young nymphs who wove it.  This peplus was carried to the temple, where it was laid on the statue of Athena.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
March 21st ~     Autumn Equinox *Celebration of the reunion of the daughter of the Earth, Kore', with her mother, Demeter.  Spring returns.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>April Aphrodite</B></H2><br>
<br>
<br>
<BR><br>
April 15th ~     Feast of Aphrodite *Feasts were held in celebration of Aphrodite.  Much merry making and love making were had.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>May Artemis</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
May 1st ~     May Day *Parades, celebrations, feasts were had.  Wear green on May Day; it is the colour our goddess of nature, Artemis, loves best, denoting reserrection and rebirth.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
May 19th thru 28th ~ Kallyntaria and Plynteria: Spring Cleaning *On this day a special effort was made to   clean the sacred statues of the goddesses and gods.   Statues were washed in the nearest river or lakes, submerging them and letting them reunite with the life-giving waters.  Afterwards, statues were dressed in their jewels and paraded back to their temples.  No singing or fun was allowed during this procedure.  The festivals were solemized because it was work and not play.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>June Hera</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
June 14th ~     Birthday of the Muses *Feasts were held and artisans and bards showed their works that were inspired by the Muses.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
June 17th ~     Marriage of Orpheus and Eurydice *Couples celebrated their unions with gifts and a big feast.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
June 21st ~     Summer Solstice *A time for wishing and magic.  Make your wishes by walking to the nearest river, ocean, bay, brook, or lake and, chanting to yourself, float a flower with your kiss upon it - traditionally a rose - into the waves to carry your wish home to Hera, Queen of the Gods.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>August Ceres</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
August 10th~     Feast of Ceres *Celebrate the coming harvest with a small feast and prayers.  Then libations are poured upon the crops in the fields to bless them.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>September The Muses</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
September 1st ~     Thargelia: Feast of the First Fruits *Feast to celebrate the harvest.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
September10th~  Feast of the Muses *Feasting and singing were joyously held in the villages.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
September 21st ~ Feast of the Divine Trinity: Rite of Eleusis *Altars are decorated with flowers, golden apples, cider, and seed cakes.  Then a great feast is held in honor of Demeter, Kore', and Iacchos (brother of Kore).<BR><br>
<BR><br>
September 23rd ~ Autumn Equinox *Celebrated with the <BR><br>
Eleusian Mysteries *Celebrated by depositing sacred objects at the feet of Demeter, women carried baskets filled with the goddess's belongs, such as a comb, a mirror, a snake figure, wheat, and barely.  Then presented them to Demeter.  Then went to bathe in the sea, put on a new linen, and poured libations on the Earth.  Then all gathered and celebrated in their best finery: the day was raucous and filled with dancing. "Hail, Demeter!" was enthusiastically shouted.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
September 28th ~ The Holy Night *All are lined up behind the solemn goddesses represented by two veiled, mourning matrons.  They drink kykeon, a hallucinogenic brew the women bring with them.  They enter the scared place Epoteia, by admission with a password.  Upon entering the people throng toward the place where a great fire was built.  Kore' now the Queen of the Underworld, appears and all bow to her.  The presence of the Goddess gave all a chance to see their own death as part of their lives and to remove fears about the afterlife.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>October Sophia</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
October 5th ~     Day of the Holy Spirit *Sophia, the spirit of female wisdom, disguised herself as a white dove, her sacred bird.  This day we celebrate the wisdom of women.  Men are not allowed at this celebration, as they have long sought to bring silence to Sophia.  So that she can no longer speak wisdom to women.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>November Hecate</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
November 16th ~     Night of Hecate *Hecate is the most ancient form of the moon goddess trinity, Artemis; the virgin; Selene, the mother,  and Hecate, the crone.  People left food out at the crossroads where three different roads met, for she was the goddess of transformation and ruled the passages of life.  It was well understood that the food was to be eaten by the poor.  <BR><br>
<BR><br>
<H2 ALIGN=Center><B>December Hestia</B></H2><br>
<br>
<BR><br>
<BR><br>
December 5th ~     Feast of Hestia *Women gathered and held a small feast in celebration of the Goddess of Hearth and Home.<BR><br>
<BR><br>
December 21st ~    Winter Solstice *Demeter gave birth to her sacred daughter, Kore' (Persephone) on this day.  The Earth Goddess gives birth to Dionysus.  Today we celebrate the rebirth of the earth and our lives on the shortest night of the year.</B></P><br>
